The Gilded Age was a time of industrialization, economic growth and cultural values of materialism. In a time where people were wearing the most expensive gold and jewelry and fabrics, I wanted to capture the irony of that in 2022 as we‚Äôre facing the climate crisis. I wanted to do something that was sustainable and up-cycled and covered with flowers because I feel like we‚Äôre remembering now that the most valuable things are the finite resources in a natural world. Thank you @prabalgurung for constantly waving your social activism and soul through your work. I was so proud to be there with you and I‚Äôm excited for us to do more together ‚ù§Ô∏è

BAM BAM FEAT . @teddysphotos  is NUMBER 5 ON THE GLOBAL CHARTS ! I‚Äôm so damn grateful. When we wrote this song we were playing songs I heard in my childhood- songs that made my family sing, dance, and celebrate life. Celia Cruz- la vida es un carnaval- Marc Anthony- vivir mi vida. Un mont√≥n de estrellas - polo monta√±√©s. These songs in Spanish have important life messages about how life can break your heart, but we can also dance and sing and move our bodies through it. This song was me coming out of pain and into joy, from girlhood to womanhood, and putting in a song the wisdom that has been passed down to me from my mom and to her from her mom. Life has its up and downs; but you will laugh again and you will love again. As my mom says, QUE ME QUITEN LO BAILAO. ‚ù§Ô∏è 
This song is a god damn family heirloom on the radio . Music is sacred. And I‚Äôm so thankful to you all for listening. ü•Çü•Çü•Ç

I just fuckin loved this moment. The fact that to do our jobs the best we can, we  gotta tap into that joy, connection with each other, and playfulness. Things have gotten so fancy and non ritualistic and sometimes disconnected from their original purpose, we forget music and art has always had a sacred and pure purpose - we were just sitting around a campfire telling stories about the human experience thru song and expressiong how we felt  thru our bodies . Always gotta remind myself that‚Äôs what it‚Äôs about when I feel tempted to feel pressure or anxious about the ‚Äúscale‚Äù  of any of it. It‚Äôs not really about any of that . That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm so proud of the fact that when writing this album it was fully sacred . Fully for ME and my collaborators. We forgot about anybody else outside of the room. Music is so much more than chart numbers, impressing people, or the scale of how many people you reach- it is sacred and a spiritual practice. (as is shakin that ass with your friends üòâ)

sometimes when I have moments of calm or beauty I hesitate to take pics of them for photo dumps because I wanna stay in the moment and keep it sacred and mine, but i love these moments alone in nature so much.. they bring me so much awe and interconnectedness and I know social media feeds can conjure up the total opposite of that - I hope I spread some calming and wonder-inspiring vibes and maybe a gentle reminder to take some time for yourself to enjoy our beautiful world. to see a sunset or a sunrise, to pause to look at a beautiful flower that you‚Äôve never seen on a street you‚Äôve walked a million times. to hear the birds chirp, feel the cold wind on your face, and know you might be walking alone in that moment, but you‚Äôre dependent and intertwined and connected with everything that‚Äôs on this living, breathing Earth

one of the biggest things i learned during the pandemic was the importance of REST. before I literally had no choice but to stop and stand still, I didn‚Äôt know what work life balance was. I felt guilty during days off because I felt like I wasn‚Äôt being productive or I could be doing more. At the same time, right before we were forced to quarantine I was completely burnt out and felt like I couldn‚Äôt do this career anymore.  Then I started seeing how after resting during that period, cultivating new hobbies, prioritizing my mental health, my friendships and relationships, making time for exercise, and also enjoying being lazy again, I started to naturally feel inspired, passionate, and way more creative. Nowadays I never feel guilty about making time for time off because I know that without rest, and time for joy, laziness, and play, I will feel burnt out, stressed, sad, and exhausted and I won‚Äôt be able to do the work I want to put out into the world. In a culture that wears exhaustion and business as a badge of honor, remember we are just animals who were meant to be roaming around the forest eating, pooping; and making babies; and in the way our society is built,  overwork is literally killing us. Culture  constantly makes us feel like we don‚Äôt do enough and we must be ‚Äúhustling‚Äù and ‚Äúgrinding‚Äù... but don‚Äôt forget that rest is honorable, necessary, and sacred. In returning to the ‚Äúnew normal‚Äù, let‚Äôs instill values in our work environments that prioritize the individual in a holistic way. We are not robots and our brains are not computers. For the sake of our health and happiness during our brief time here on earth, the societal structures of work and how it relates to an individual‚Äôs mental health need an upgrade. Recently, I had the honor and privilege to visit families and children seeking asylum at the U.S.-Mexico border. As an immigrant myself, this experience was truly humbling. Being able to listen to these families and children tell their stories helped me understand their journeys and opened my heart to what we can all be doing to help. These parents have some of the same hopes and dreams for their children as my mom had for me when we left Cuba. Our stories started out in search of a better life but timing created two completely different outcomes.

We have the opportunity to really reimagine how we can protect some of our most vulnerable communities and ensure that people desperately seeking help at our border are welcomed with love and dignity. 

Thank you to @thisisabouthumanity, @immdef_lawcenter, @fwdus, @yeswecanwf, and Caritas shelter for your tireless advocacy on behalf of these families. Follow them to learn more and stay informed on how you can help. Head to my stories for more information ‚ù§Ô∏è #thisisabouthumanity #welcomewithdignity

#DontGoYet is the first song from my next album, Familia. The album‚Äôs journey started with @scottharris123 and our makeshift studio in my bedroom in Miami about a year ago. We just had a mic, some MIDI keyboards and guitars! Then we brought it to LA where I met and worked with @mikesabath for the first time. That first day of working together, we wrote this song after listening to old Cuban songs and playing with my dog Tarzan. Then  @rickyreed (who side-gigs as my therapist sometimes LOL) put his sauce alllll over it. These guys have become my true friends and we created a really loving and inspiring creative space. This whole album to me was inspired by two things: family and food. Your family by blood, but also your chosen family. Who you want to break bread with. Who you want to sit at the dinner table with, cook a meal for, get wine-drunk with, and dance in the living room with.  To me, those are the moments that make me glad to be alive, those moments  of collective joy and true vulnerability and connection with other people. Moments where the food you cooked together feeds your soul and so does the laughter, conversation, and emotional intimacy. I hope you enjoy it and I hope it inspires many wine drunk kitchen dance parties for you and your familia.

as humans, our brains and the way we process the world around us is so incredible, yet complex. Children especially are resilient but there are so many kids across the world going through different challenges and traumas on a daily basis. They spend each day developing, learning, and absorbing from their surroundings and those moments have an impact. 

For me, I had many experiences growing up in Cuba and Mexico, immigrating to the US, figuring out how to mix in with American society, and also leaving home to pursue a music career and being in the spotlight at a young age. There were lots of ups and downs and it took me a long time to realize how those experiences affected my mental health as an adult. 

Over the past year, I‚Äôve been lucky to speak with and learn from the incredible @nadineburkeharris who has been leading the research of Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs). Her work is so powerful and teaches that although these experiences might happen to us they don‚Äôt need to define us.¬† It takes a lot of self-work, asking for help and resources to work through these things and grow üíï

This past year was full of heartbreaking challenges & uncertainty. We‚Äôve faced a global pandemic, economic disruption- shining a light on centuries of systemic oppression, & so much more. 2020 was a time of constant reflection for many of us & I‚Äôve been honest with myself about how I was showing up or not showing up in the world. Over the past couple of months, Ana Perez & Jerry Tello from the @la.cultura.cura have been guiding me on this journey filled with learning & unpacking the ways I have contributed to systems & beliefs that actively oppress others, whether by making insensitive comments in the past or by being a bystander, & growing to acknowledge the missteps along the way as I work to become a true ally.

This is a lifelong process but this awareness has helped me commit to doing whatever I can to be a part of positive change. There‚Äôs much more to do but if you are interested in learning about racial healing or hearing about my experience, tune in to my conversation today with Jerry during the National Day of Racial Healing virtual event.
Through this work, I‚Äôve learned a lot about the challenges faced by our communities. And while we all struggled with the events that transpired from the last year, there were activists on the frontlines of those transformative moments carrying the trauma of the unjust systems some groups face everyday. To be a part of this positive change, we have a responsibility to support organizers to care for themselves as they advocate to move our society forward. Through my ongoing reflection, I committed to learning about how we can make these resources accessible to those who need it.

That‚Äôs also why I am honored to partner with @movementvoterproject to launch the Healing Justice Project to provide funding for mental wellness resources for activists across the country. We hope to support these grassroots organizers in their tireless advocacy - thank you to all the activists that have continued to show up for us time & time again. We see you, we hear you, & we are here for you üíï

I'll be highlighting some of these incredible organizers in the coming months. Head to my stories to learn more about the Healing Justice Project!

I‚Äôve learned a lot about love with this guy. It‚Äôs not just the happy blissful moments you see in pictures and videos- When you‚Äôre in a relationship with someone, it feels like they are this mirror reflecting yourself back to you-  I constantly have to confront my fears, my anxieties,  my insecurities, my patterns of thinking, my beliefs about life and about myself. It‚Äôs not as simple as it looks in pictures sometimes. sometimes, it‚Äôs messy and uncomfortable and ugly lol. But there‚Äôs nothing like the pull, the FORCE that is love, to be the light in the darkness- to be the gravitational pull that gives you the relentless strength to be braver,wiser, and better than you were yesterday. It‚Äôs so instinctive for us to love, even if our minds try to protect us from it sometimes, but our nature as humans is to love. And to be in love means to choose that person over and over again, to go through the messy stuff with. And that‚Äôs way more beautiful and raw and real than perfection. I‚Äôm all for being vulnerable on social media because I think only the neatness and perfection of life is shown on here; and that can make us all feel extra lonely and weird! So raise your glass to the messiness and weirdness of being human and the miracle. And the easiness. And the instinct. And the  relentless force that is love.

I didn‚Äôt vote for a Democrat or a Republican. I voted for character, decency, justice, TRUTH and TRUST in the leader of our nation. I voted for a President that believes in goodness, who will protect the morals and values of this country, and not betray them. I voted for a land of opportunity, regardless of where you come from or what you look like. I voted for someone that believes families belong together and children should be in schools, not cages. I voted for real leadership and a belief in the America I want to see. 

Right now, our votes mean more than they ever have before. We have a choice to swear someone into office who believes in us; we have a choice to elect a leader that follows the science and values the lives of the American people. This is our chance to be a part of history, to be the generation that creates real and lasting change, but that change only happens if we show up and make our voices heard by casting our ballots. 

I voted for someone who is not in it for himself, but is in it for every one of us. Someone who doesn‚Äôt take pleasure in dividing us, but one who works hard to bring us together. That‚Äôs why I voted for @JoeBiden and @KamalaHarris. 
 
If you haven‚Äôt already voted, confirm your polling location, check what IDs you need to bring, and make sure your voice is heard! For more information about voting in your area, head to iwillvote.com! #TodosConBiden #BidenHarris

meditation has changed my life in the last few months. I didn‚Äôt share this with you guys at the time because honestly I was just trying to be okay, but I was experiencing severe anxiety. it was meditation- it was practicing every single day multiple times a day that has been healing me, and, more than just helping me manage strong emotions like anxiety and stress, it‚Äôs making me a better human.  not only  does it help in times like this with stress and anxiety, meditation is the practice of strengthening habits like empathy, love, and compassion- making you feel more connected to not only everybody around you , but living beings in general like animals, plants,  and the earth, which is a living being, itself. In times like these, especially as young people, even if we are healthy, it‚Äôs important to practice compassion and help others that could be suffering. We are in this together, let‚Äôs not be indifferent to others risk. it‚Äôs our responsibility to do whatever it takes to keep everyone safe. Empathy to others‚Äô reality and solidarity could make the difference in hard moments like this. 
We can‚Äôt think that we will be unaffected because we feel young and healthy. we have parents, grandparents, friends, and  neighbors, and we don‚Äôt want to be a part of the problem when we could be part of the solution. So I‚Äôd like you to take 10 minutes of your day today to either look up loving kindness meditation on Calm or YouTube. Or just follow these instructions: close your eyes and sit with your spine upright and feel gravity grounding your body to the earth‚Äôs surface and supporting you. Take three deep breaths and then begin to just notice the natural flow of your breath. Being aware of breathing in, breathing out. Following every inhale and exhale with your attention. Once your mind has stilled. Picture every human in the world right now, elders, people that have respiratory problems and are vulnerable, picture the people that are vulnerable, picture their families, and say ‚ÄúMay you be healthy. May you be safe. May you be free from illness. May you be well.‚Äù Repeat until you really feel it in your heart ‚ù§Ô∏è- love you guys, please stay safe !

all of us go through the same things and are trying to figure it out - none of us are exempt from stress, anxiety, sadness, pain, and countless other internal struggles, whether it‚Äôs moments of it, or longer than just moments - for me, i suffered from anxiety so much that I had no choice but to change, to look for different tools that could help me, because it was bringing me so much pain- the last few months especially, I‚Äôve worked so hard on this and am experiencing so much growth - which means, to anybody struggling, that growth and change is completely possible ! But today I just want to share this loving kindness meditation that is my favorite thing I‚Äôve learned so far- because it‚Äôs easy to forget in our own struggles (I‚Äôve been guilty of this and that‚Äôs why I love this particular practice so much) that everybody around us, and on this planet is fighting their own battle, and is feeling their own pain - some at a way more excruciating level than others, and therefore, EVERYBODY, even the people that most piss you off, are in DESPERATE need of love and kindness - I hope you try this practice today : for 10 minutes I breathe and picture somebody I love and say these phrases, I picture them happy and smiling as if it‚Äôs the best day of their lives, I picture them sad and wish them with all my heart that they be free from it - then I picture myself and say them about myself, then someone I‚Äôm not as close to (or someone you don‚Äôt get along with so much), and then I picture all the humans on the planet, and then all animals and living beings too- it really makes me feel connected and not alone , because the truth is - we never are, we‚Äôre all in it together . ‚ù§Ô∏è

one of the most gorgeous experiences I‚Äôve ever had. the desert to me was something mystical and almost not real, something I saw in movies but my brain didn‚Äôt register as a real place, almost like when you see insane places that look like paintings on planet earth - we got to ride on the dunes and then stay overnight, I woke up to go to the bathroom at 3 and saw stars like I‚Äôve never seen in my life!!! never in my life did I think I would see a place like this, I urge anyone to save up to travel, and not like a beach/ resort type thing, but to a place that couldn‚Äôt be more different than what you know - it changes your life and mind in every way possible and is one of (and arguably the most) the greatest, most humbling adventures of living. getting to see places like this just makes me desperate  to see more
